ReconNameMissileDesc=342_06/06
ReconPTMissileDesc=57E7-Y Surface to Air Missile Emplacement.
ReconFTMissileDesc=SPECIFICATIONS:\nA surface-to-air missile armed with a 14 kg fragmentation rod warhead. The missile has a tandem, bicaliber body: separable booster and sustainer. The warhead, contact fuse, and proximity fuse are located in the sustainer. At launch, the missile weighs 55 kg.  With a range of 1 to 16 km, it has a maximum speed of 1,200 meters per second. The 57E7-Y is officially still in the prototype stage.

ReconName3_2AF_A=322_01/01
ReconPT3_2AF_A=SUBJECT:	Americium 239\nUPLOADED:	6/11/04\nSOURCE:		Grimsdottir\n\nATOMIC NUMBER:	95\nATOMIC WEIGHT:	u243\nMELTING POINT:	K 1268\nBOILING POINT:	K 2880\nHEAT OF FUSION:	kJ/mol 14.4
ReconFT3_2AF_A=SUBJECT:\nSummary of the weapons potentiality of Americium 239\n\nFound in trace amounts in most fire detectors, Americium is a man-made element that can be used in the construction of nuclear devices.  The principle isotope is Americium 241, created as a result of the decay of plutonium 241. Americium 239 is substantially less pure, but still within weapons grade.\n\nAmericium 239 has a high rate of spontaneous fission, meaning that it is continuously throwing off excess neutrons. A nuclear bomb is normally detonated by a pulse of neutrons. A lower-grade weapon, such as an Americium device, runs the risk of being prematurely detonated (by a few milliseconds) by background neutrons. This can substantially reduce the yield, but a 1-kiloton device could still result in a destructive radius roughly half the size of Hiroshima.(author: Grimsdottir)

ReconName3_2AF_B=321_01/02
ReconPT3_2AF_B=SUBJECT:	Nadezhda\nUPLOADED:	------\nSOURCE:		Grimsdottir\n\n
ReconFT3_2AF_B=DESCRIPTION:\nA fragment of a message recovered from enemy data The letter is from Nadezhda management to all employees explaining that the Russian Military will be on site for an undisclosed time.\n\nTEXT:\nNadezhda Nuclear Power Co.\n\nAll Staff:\nPlease excuse the inconvenience over the next few weeks of a visit from the Russian Military. Plant directors have received a communication from Moscow requesting our full cooperation. We intend to comply.\n\nThough our soldiers' purpose at Nadezhda is by no means "top-secret," we have been asked not to speak of their presence any more than is absolutely necessary. Please refrain from mentioning any military activities to your family, colleagues, etc.\n\nAll staff should cooperate fully with any requests made by Russian military personnel, but do not engage any soldier in conversation unless prompted.\n\nThank-you for your understanding.\n\n- Plant Direction

ReconName5_1AF_B=511_03/03
ReconPT5_1AF_B=SUBJECT:	Ark Interrogation File\nUPLOADED:	11/11/04\nSOURCE:		Grimsdottir\n
ReconFT5_1AF_B=DESCRIPTION:\nCristavi's men interrogated one of Nikoladze's colonels for information on the Ark. The 8-hour ordeal was videotaped and transcribed.  I've pulled the most relevant bits from the resulting document.\n\nTEXT:\nHOUR 5\n\nINTERROGATOR 1:	We can't stop until you tell us.\n\nSUBJECT:	(scream) ...blind.\n\nINTERROGATOR 2:	Just tell us what it is. What's the Ark? It won't hurt anything to talk. They're just words.\n\nSUB:		Oh God. Jesus Mary.\n\nINT2:		Listen, we only want\n\nSUB:		It's a SADM.\n\nINT2:		A Sadam?\n\nSUB:		Special Atomic Demolitions Munitions.\n\nINT2:		Good, that's very good.\n\nHOUR 7\n\nINT1:		Where?\n\nSUB:		There's a vault (scream) In the library. Just make it stop.\n\nHOUR 8\n\nSUB:		I swear! It's not!\n\nINT2:		Convince us.\n\n
ReconFT5_1AF_B1=SUB:		What can I do? (scream)\n\nINT1:		Security only makes sense.\n\nSUB:		It's locked! Retinal scanner! (scream) I can't. Locked, but no booby traps. I can see my. God.  (scream)\n\nINT2:		I think we've lost him.\n\nEND TRANSCRIPTION

ReconNameCall911AF=221_01/02
ReconPTCall911AF=SUBJECT:	Phone Transcript\nUPLOADED:	1/11/04\nSOURCE:		Grimsdottir\n\n
ReconFTCall911AF=DESCRIPTION:\nFollowing is a transcription of a telephone call between Anna Grimsdottir and an unidentified Georgian mercenary, alias "Ivan."\n\nTEXT:\n\nAG:	911 Emergency.\n\nIVAN:	What the hell? I've been transferred 3 times. This is an emergency!\n\nAG:	Sir, are you in immediate danger?\n\nIVAN:	Yes I'm in danger! They're going (static)\n\nAG:	Are you still there, sir? Hello?\n\nIVAN:	Yes! You've got to help me! I can tell your government things.\n\nAG:	What's your location? \n\nIVAN:	The Kalinatek Building. You have to hurry. I triggered a fire alarm.\n\nAG:	Sir?\n\nIVAN:	What I'm saying is that I'm safe for now, they can't get through the fire doors, but when they figure it out I'm dead!\n\nAG:	Can I have your name, sir?\n\n
ReconFTCall911AF1=IVAN:	What? Um. Call me Ivan. Listen, tell your government I'm valuable.\n\nAG:	Sir?\n\nIVAN:	I work for these people. The Georgians. Kombayn Nikoladze. I know things.\n\nAG:	If you'd like to tell me\n\nIVAN:	Ha! Get me out alive, and I talk. Until then nothing.\n\nEND

ReconNameProgDesc=342_03/06
ReconPTProgDesc=SUBJECT:	Pickett Gap Program\nUPLOADED:	9/11/2004\nSOURCE:		Grimsdottir
ReconFTProgDesc=DESCRIPTION:\nPhilip Masse' 'Pickett Gap' program is targeted to sabotage the water filtration system in the small town of Pickett Gap, Tennessee. The water filtration plant has bypassed several outdated sections of piping suspected of Cryptosporidium bacterium and installed a UV disinfectant system as backup. INTEL indicates that Masse has a logic bomb that could scramble the UV system and redirect the water supply through the tainted pipes.\n\nSince we know about it, we can be there as it happens. Masse' programs seem to share a few core components, but we haven't examined any yet because they're self-destructive on execution. If I can watch one in action, I think I should be able to see how it works then kill it before anybody gets hurt. And if we figure out one program, we've figured them all. It's a gamble, but I think it's one worth taking. (Author: Grimsdottir)

ReconNameUSAF=133_04/04
ReconPTUSAF=SUBJECT:	USAF SR-71 archived reports\nUPLOADED:	27/10/04\nSOURCE:		Grimsdottir\n
ReconFTUSAF=DESCRIPTION:\nFollowing is a transcription of a fragment of a radio message intercepted by an SR-71 pilot and an AWACS control aircraft over the Caspian Sea.\n\n\nAWACS:	-any entrances to the hub?\n\nSR-71:	(static) some kind of automated blast door (static)\n\nAWACS:	(static) data hub (static)\n\nSR-71:	(static) appears to be one window into the hub (static)\n\nEND INTERCEPT
